04087nam a22006855i 9781400834600DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20102010nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008346007 a10.1515/97814008346002doi  a(DE-B1597)453710  a(OCoLC)979954316  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aREL1020002bisacsh  aCC 66002rvk0(DE-625)rvk/17661:1 aJohnston, Mark, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSurviving Death /cMark Johnston.  aCourse Book 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2010] 4cÂ©2010  a1 online resource (408 p.) :b2 line illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCarl G. Hempel Lecture Series ;v100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tChapter One. Is Heaven a Place We Can Get To? -- tChapter Two. On the Impossibility of My Own Death -- tChapter Three. From Anatta to Agape -- tChapter Four. What Is Found at the Center? -- tChapter Five. A New Refutation of Death -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this extraordinary book, Mark Johnston sets out a new understanding of personal identity and the self, thereby providing a purely naturalistic account of surviving death. Death threatens our sense of the importance of goodness. The threat can be met if there is, as Socrates said, "something in death that is better for the good than for the bad." Yet, as Johnston shows, all existing theological conceptions of the afterlife are either incoherent or at odds with the workings of nature. These supernaturalist pictures of the rewards for goodness also obscure a striking consilience between the philosophical study of the self and an account of goodness common to Judaism, Christianity, Hinduism, and Buddhism: the good person is one who has undergone a kind of death of the self and who lives a life transformed by entering imaginatively into the lives of others, anticipating their needs and true interests. As a caretaker of humanity who finds his or her own death comparatively unimportant, the good person can see through death. But this is not all. Johnston's closely argued claims that there is no persisting self and that our identities are in a particular way "Protean" imply that the good survive death. Given the future-directed concern that defines true goodness, the good quite literally live on in the onward rush of humankind. Every time a baby is born a good person acquires a new face.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aDeath. 0aFuture life. 0aRELIGIONvTheology. 7aRELIGION / Theology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978140083460040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400834600423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400834600.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK